A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by affirming that election fraud in the US is less frequent than the number of people killed by lightning.
The Republican lawyers have, by the way, recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the US in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, some of these measures undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting the elections in each country.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that make the registration or registration procedure more difficult.
This phenomenon has become more important after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, which restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as voters on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a judicial act is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state asked voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a request.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Law in 2008.
The Republican authorities have hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted legislation in 34 states that force voters to display a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million persons entitled to vote, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new voters do not have such an ID card in 2012.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to get the required ID.
Young people, minorities and low-income people are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID.
That goes even further.
Students who are regarded as voters, who increasingly vote for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who choose more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws calling on voters to demonstrate their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic votes.
For it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators promoted laws in eight states in 2011, which abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns to register voters in the general elections in 2004 have helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the number of new voters registered by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they represent only 13% of the state's voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of the voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The US Advocate General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws that require a photo ID to be shown.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the passed laws and see them as a clear goal of influencing the results in the countries that are decisive for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that have passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral panel to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these amendments to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, some of these measures undermine the democratic system of the United States.
