The Higgs boson analyzed
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson last summer caused a certain stir, and for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or least false explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
Without the shadow of doubt, we know that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics congress in Kyoto this week, but there is still a lack of data to be completely secure about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that it is actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let us look at what it is about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that causes two objects to not be present in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli's exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", whereby this "state" consists largely of some of its properties.
From this the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner there are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle in a way.
And in the other, the bosons, a bad bond of anarchists, who have nothing sacred - definitely not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this place, like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disorder" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disrupted" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must achieve very high energies, a little similar to a frozen pond whose surface could only be shattered by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - is required to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
There are in fact not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator by itself.
And equally not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these researches be "good", asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine in detail all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who are eagerly hoping that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great defects, since it does not explain gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there were none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous stroke laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was regarded as a "laboratory game" at the beginning.
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... 的 Le Devoir
With its Committee on Deaths in Dignity, Quebec has recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
Prostate cancer, which consumed him, had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he resigns to let himself be helped with the meal.
Bravely, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing standing," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois's home.
Returning to the childhood phase is unacceptable humiliation for certain persons.
"That depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards, he notes.
In the opinion of several people who work in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these regressions.
The patients who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, doctors and nurses who take care of them no longer overwhelm them with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and through suffocation".
But through the illness, I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any more wishes in life," she says, before accepting that she is wearing a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, she still expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provide personal care and help with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if you take into account that one day we'll all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
You give the dying person a mouth care with Brandy or Pepsi as desired.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served Mr. X a beer that died over the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," says Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
There's no day like the other at Victor-Gadbois's.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family reunion in the yard and is well supported by his pillows while being exposed in his honor, a young man of 36 who is surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years of age," says Dr. Christiane Martel with concern.
53% of the patients admitted to the home of Victor-Gadbois come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. a care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal area, are more or less specializing exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec's healthcare system that has led several specialists in palliative care to look forward to adopting a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by prominent figures of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's healthcare system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without taking any action to alleviate her.
I fear that the only reason patients want to die is because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients until the last day despite the worst predictions.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped arduous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she replied that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not accepting this wish after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care in Montreal's home palliative care society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in either sporadically or permanently tossing the patient until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated, all say the same sentence, "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be eased."
