Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as the Credits, which are used to advance in a video game that can be won or bought by games (and sometimes exchanged back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the invoice book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins traded are present in the public accounts accounting book spread throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, whereby the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, has the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a dismemberment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The aim is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check whether it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay with the same money twice (less than 10 minutes) for cheating, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other will remain without linking, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but divisible to a hundred millionths, leaving some room for manoeuvre...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement of the computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites providing services to Bitcoin were attacked and Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, a company that is paying with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analysed the accounting book and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega lock sale" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the Coinabul company, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend whereby hierarchical systems are reconsidered in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
Moreover, the ECB's report provides for a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be high in the event of the success of this currency.
