A Constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever with regard to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on one map.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this plenary two additional months to complete his work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been based on a provisional text which has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and creating legal confusion.
This new initiative has only created an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "put right underfoot".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way of ending the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
It is also a way for the President to regain his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is raging throughout the country.
According to an interview with the American weekly magazine Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote favourably.
Especially since an ultimatum is given to the Egyptian people with this recourse to a hasty vote: "You either vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 largely Islamist members of this constituent assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the liberals did not comply with the request.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they believe that they have not been able to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities and civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in all haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were usually adopted unanimously.
Incidentally, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day was expressed in the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention, finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made more strict application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who see this only as a propaganda strike, reply to "devilness."
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which recognises the University of Al-Azhar as an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people who are invited to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
One can see here the first signs of a theocracy".
The fears of the liberals are also nourished by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"Currently, no concrete religious commitment can be seen.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, "that there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised of the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue: the powers of the army.
In line with the military's wish, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights organisations have called for.
The latter also share their fears about the text which they consider to be liberating.
Blasphemy is maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no more article refers to the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel Ukrainian tourists expect sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and unspoiled nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons for visiting Israel.
Bowing to the Sacred Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding celebration, walking on the water, the suckling of the sea storm and fishing.
Here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries, however, are located in Jerusalem.
Believers here follow the path of suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path starts at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world that symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most holy place of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in the year 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave there notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a journey to the heights
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in the year 25 AD.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at an altitude of 450 metres above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins by their own strength.
All others bring a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, where it attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the mountaintop.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited on just one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls of the Dead Sea, found in rock caves in the Judean desert, are kept, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso will be exhibited there.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the monument to the children built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room, there is total darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the lands in which they died sound.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathed there all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salinity and thus even carries non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and medicinal sludge as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm damaged nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia ran through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda here, with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, which are named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is held by all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Tonight evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Listed list for tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your bad English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money on the trip is rather not taken in euros, but in dollars, which can simply be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a expressway and in Haifa the only underground line of the country with six stations, which connects the lower city with the upper city.
Actually, it's an underground funicular.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which includes transfers for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, marine products, fish without sheds and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you can choose between different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls made from puree beans and peas (Falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this there are many well-fed cats, who stray comfortably and undisturbed through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between $37 a day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an extra $15 a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, prior to the lifting of the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading with fake certificates
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in the home.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme only applies to migrants wishing to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory in the future for all migrant workers.
In doing so, one must not only pass language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law also excludes persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Purpose, problem and protection of rights
All the examination bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship with Peoples, the Moscow State University, the St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; more than 160 centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to launch the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law came into force in the press: What is the point of the whole thing?
What are the changes in the rule of language skills for both the Russians and the migrant workers?
In particular, according to spokesman of the Migration Authority, the aim was to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, Head of the Representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected from their departure.
Only organized recruitment will 90% solve the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without work, education, language skills and medical assessment face problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who will put him in a dark, narrow barracks under the pretext of help, where he will endure without food and documents with dozens of his equal months and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"In your home, you will be promised one thing, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be taken off, and you will not receive the promised wage," confirms Tolib Schwaripov, head of the Central Employment Migration Administration of the Tajik Migration Authority.
Don't scold, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they are not only not able to speak the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the migrant workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Free access for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
Russian police personnel know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and that results in cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says the Tajike Umed Hushkadamov to journalists.
"Don't worry about the cost of false papers"
Already on the day that the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants could be falsified.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary ink printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests in this way paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that certificates cannot be bought easily.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time that they receive time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Ministry of the Interior ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in crime extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten the law on arms for private arms owners.
The authorities are responding to recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead during the rampage of Moscow lawyer Dmitri Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the use of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Corruption, Irina Jarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, the authors of which - representatives of various arms associations - call on the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percentage of crimes involving registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed over the course of six months in 2012, while for the same period a total of 1,168 thousand offences were recorded.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private arms owners will not prevent criminals from using themselves on the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, any weapon for little money can be found in Moscow.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel, there are illegal weapons stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen from both the police armory and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Many military camps often had explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases involved arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, weapons manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
"Nowadays, there are countless private armament factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore throw weapons under hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," says the expert.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is its own, sometimes artisanal production, as well as a mafia that organizes smuggling," the former military member explains.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Government Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminal literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
According to the investigators, most of the illegal weapons come from the army and legal services.
Half of all weapons on the black market were there because of the "debt of those responsible for their work with weapons," the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% from thefts in weapons production, and 5% from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at an arms store who does not want to be named assures that weapons found during illegal excavations have long been bought by no one, since they are outdated.
According to him, it's more common for traders to get supplies in a weapons store.
An ensign buys a gun, such as a TT-type gun.
The gun is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, periodically carry out control purchases from traders offering illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
Buyers and sellers find each other most often through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone came to my attention and suggested that I come to the Begowaja station, where a person would wait for me to take me to a certain place where we could negotiate the price.
The prize for the gun I only learned there
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have an acquaintance like that, but I don't trust him."
There are merchants in the markets, but there you have to go and arrange with a code like "Ivan Ivanovich, who tells that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I'm even getting some punch rings from a friend I trust at the moment.
He's also giving me the hit rings because he knows I don't rat him out.
Newbies are looking for weapons in different ways.
