In the past few days, massive protests against low wages have taken place in Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will swell further or whether they will soon run out of air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organisations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of simple Walmart and fast-food workers, the protest organizers pursue the goal of establishing trade unions.
Up to now, this sector of the economy is hardly organized by trade unions.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, on the so-called Black Friday, where sales took place in the US, attracting millions of customers, which sometimes led to crowds of hands.
On this day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, stopped their work and, together with trade unions and left-wing activists, struck branches of the chain whose target group are low and middle-income people.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The commodity in Walmart stores is on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
This is why many of the slightly paid Walmart employees only buy in at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart can often only sell the goods so cheaply because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklifts or hand scanners.
The participants in the protests at Black Friday demanded wage increases and expressed their anger at the fact that the contribution to the company's health insurance had increased from 30 to 100 dollars a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour cannot afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from California University in Berkeley prove that if the company raises the average wage to 12 dollars an hour, it would cost Walmart 3.2 billion dollars.
This is about 1.1% more than they are now donating for wages.
If Walmart were to completely transfer the wage increases to the customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
That would be $12.39 a year for them compared to today's additional spending.
Supporters of Walmart are pleased to note that only nine states have protested and that they have not caused any losses to the company.
The Black Friday lasted in its store from 8 o'clock in the evening on Thursday to midnight the next day, and during this period Walmart sold about 5000 items per second.
All in all, the Walmart casks carried out nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company's spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post that "less than five" Walmart employees put down the work and that the protest action was merely "an additional PR trick" of the union that organized the protests.
"Free cashier!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where, however, their destination was not Walmart branches (which are not wanted in this advanced city and are therefore so far non-existent), but McDonald's and other affordable restaurants.
McDonald's says the company is selling billions of servings, and yet you're not being given sick days, and you're not being paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, member of the New York City Council
Currently, according to federal and New York legislation, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour.
In fast-food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too strong, and on average, their simple employees in New York get $8.90 an hour.
Less than they deserve no one in this expensive city.
How it is possible to get along with so little money in New York is incomprehensible to me.
There was once a time when almost a quarter of all U.S. youths were behind the counter after school at McDonald's, but the youth still lived with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw it as the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, during interviews with McDonald's staff, I constantly meet people who complain that they are getting along with this salary and sometimes even have to feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the Wall Street Journal's forum, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began on Thursday at 6.30 a.m. in front of McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and cooks from fast food restaurants receive a minimum wage of $15 per hour, more than a doubling of the current minimum wage.
They continued to demand the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
The US law prohibits corporate governance from standing in the way of this goal and from admonishing or dismissing union members.
On the other hand, corporate management does not make it easy for them.
The creation of trade unions in the fast-food sector is also difficult for objective reasons.
The most important reason is the high staff turnover.
Dissatisfied
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The highlight of the protests was a meeting at noon in front of McDonald's at Times Square, where some local democrats spoke, including city councilman Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says it's selling billions of servings, and yet you're not given sick days, and you're not paid for your honest work!"
The demonstrators were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, such as mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should work together to support the fast food workers so that they can get a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!".
According to the New York Times, this was the biggest action of its kind in the history of the US fast food industry.
However, only a few hundred people were on the ground, by far not all of whom are employed in the fast-food industry, where tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet clear whether the spark of these protests will mobilize whole masses.
"Until now, the brain can only be outsmarted moderately"
The subject of expanded reality, popular with followers of modern technologies, is usually perceived in recent times by the lens of special glasses.
First Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a corresponding patent.
In a conversation with the head of the interactive 3D technology group at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear, however, that the glasses were only a transit station for the company's scientists.
It appeals to the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and to create virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to expand the limits of this interaction.
So far, mankind has largely been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to look ahead 5-10 years and anticipate the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else can we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, a lot of things still take place on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We're trying to change this, working on real three-dimensional display systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much easier.
And first of all, we should get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- It is certainly not the universal solution, because it raises questions about privacy, because one does not always want to inform all bystanders about his actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and scarce gestures rather than extended gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gestures and language.
- How so?
- We'd ask you, for example, to hand over this bubble can to you?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- Normally, I'm just saying it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can afford at the time and what can't?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the development of new types of sensors, which will enable us to capture people's reactions more closely.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer a good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What requirements do you place on modern cameras based on your work with Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or anything else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps wouldn't be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the X- and the Y-, but also along the Z-axis must be taken into account.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The movements of man are extremely dynamic and, frankly, the current 30 fps are too little for gestures in particular.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our Redmond laboratory with a adjustable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction between man and machine.
For my work, I needed exactly such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera inclinations to determine how this helps us to determine a position in three-dimensional terms.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public, unlike Google.
Don't you think that with regard to the application of the technology of expanded reality in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it's not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand on the way, but I think the best option would be a "changing" extended reality where we could switch from glasses to smartphones via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and this is their strength (privates can only see you), but also their weakness, because an extended reality by means of glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point to: There is no palpable reaction!
The hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that expanded reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could certainly be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection document.
It perceives pressure perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are actually aimed at giving the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasonic beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is at the moment still so weak as someone was blowing over the handballs.
There are also bands for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, also that is a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outsmart the brain?
Make it think that it feels what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea. We haven't tried that yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person physically in a closed room believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), mobile platforms and large balls.
So far, the brain can only be outsmarted moderately, and we still have many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: We are only at the beginning of many topics.
