Birth in Space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth dwellers on board are looking for a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, is the important question raised as to how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
In my opinion, there are no many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least inhabit hypothetically.
"Mars and Venus," says the research assistant at the Astronomical Sternberg Institute, Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, the surface of Venus has a temperature of 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first dealt with the question of reproduction in space with regard to flora.
Half a century before that, experiments were carried out with plants.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from the terrestrial species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent to space to investigate how weightlessness affects embryo development.
A normal chick develops.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find a hold; it must be able to stand on its feet and begin to move," explains Vladimir Sychew, head of the laboratory at the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems (RAN).
Without solid ground, the chicks turned wild.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later, they just died.
"Twice we had chicks hatched and then set the whole thing up because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychew observes for the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last incubator with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, on the biosatellite "Bion" there will be only same-sex species.
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special has been found.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," notes Vladimir Sychew.
After the landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space could not be solved so far.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans could do that in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
From ethical considerations such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
There was the greatest risk of Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Will it survive the space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," says Raumfahrtveteran Watschnadse.
In June 1964, only one year after her space flight, Valentina Tereshkova, the first female cosmonaut, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andriyan Nikolaev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaja, who was twice in orbit and even did work outside the spacecraft, bore a son.
Still, there's a risk.
We only have very few cosmonauts, where everything went well after long flights and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even when flying into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Waleri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
Yet humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydro laboratory in the cosmonauts' preparation centre is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a suspended state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Even if adults feel that water is pleasant, it is an alien environment; but infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders bear witness that life on the land emanated from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the amniotic fluid for about 9 months in the womb of the mother, and that it can get used to water more easily.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth until the first swim only two weeks pass.
"This is too little time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
Thus, while weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman does not get along without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles recede enormously quickly and thus the ability to squeeze out the child also decreases.
All right, let's avoid this by birth-inducing aids.
Birth, for example, could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze out the child.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Waleri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the earth's attraction, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in a stress suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is of fundamental importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we are undertaking together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely unadapted person," predicts the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestov.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it becomes reality when the Earth's inhabitants in their spaceships set out to become a distant planet that becomes home to their all-born offspring.
NKÚ chief: control of the black system fails due to political fault
The Czech Republic has good control bodies and adequate laws in relation to public contracts, but is lagging behind in its application.
In the discussion for Aktuálně.cz this is said by the Vice-President of the Supreme Supervisory Authority (Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad, NKÚ), Miloslav Kala.
"A law is never perfect, but it has to be applied correctly - and I do not think this is the case with us," says Kala, commenting on the current situation.
A similar result appears to be a joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative example of practice, he cites the attitude of Prime Minister Petr Nečas towards the so-called "black system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls - is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then it is not easy for the chairman of the government to come, and the supervisory authority, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, to hinder its activity," says Kala.
At the meeting of the Control Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries regarding public contracts were compared.
What was that about in concrete terms?
This is a parallel test that we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, it is a question of European legislation determining how public contracts can be handled, based on national legislation, and finally, there is the actual practical application.
We have compared all of this with each other, and although the test has not yet been completed, we have found very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "stricter and perfect", but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to establish new and more precise rules over and over again. One also has to deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What results from this project for you?
It is precisely this joint control that could help us stop trying to perfect the laws and reduce and balance thresholds, if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Economic efficiency means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding illegal enrichment or even criminal acts.
But the lowering of thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we will also achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we only burden the system with excessive "paperwork" and those looking for gaps in the system have made it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
They talk about the problems with the practical implementation of the Czech Procurement Act.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is there a similar authority to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Bundesrechnungshof, which is similar to ours and also has a college which is only formed a little differently. However, in principle, both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also to some extent comparable, but Germany is a federal state, i.e. there are these audit courts also in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The FRG is only allowed to control federal funds, which corresponds to our state resources.
Public funds, which are administered by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the national audit offices.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would hate to compare this without any specific information. Nevertheless, Germany is often referred to as an example in some respects, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that perhaps because the examiners are better there?
I don't think so, but as I said, I don't like making comparisons like that.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a model for us also face problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have any cooperation with our authority, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what significance did the amendment of the public procurement law have for your authority, do you feel any impact?
Given that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an effect on our tests.
Since our checks are carried out retrospectively, we have to expect some delay.
So far, we are more likely to experience effects in the preparation phase of future controls - so we have introduced the new control tool "recognition of risks of inefficiency" and with this nearly 14,000 public contracts examined and analysed - here the changes will naturally have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law more positively, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be complied with.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to an audit are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational regional policy programme, the Regional Council) to ensure that any non-compliance with the public procurement law is equivalent to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even more stringent?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system only puts bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
First of all, let us say which way is not a good one.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what does that mean exactly?
Is the black system now prohibited or permitted?
A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then it is not easy for the chairman of the government to come and the supervisory authority, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, to hinder its activity.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the matter," but he can't say that we act as if nothing were there.
The public procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is also right for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best bid is excluded solely because of formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I believe is missing.
