Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to collect positive energy
What do you think about the end of the world taking place in less than a month?
This is one of those reports of disasters that we humans so much like to start on.
With our band The Tap Tap we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It's a nationwide benefit event that we've been planning for two years.
To this end, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, whose end is predicted for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously from 21:00 in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
The end of the concerts is said to be around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which lies in a time zone 12 hours before us.
Who made this idea?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
In doing so, we not only want to collect enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we once handed this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and keyrings against the end of the world, with the purchase of which people can also support us via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, together with other performers, also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world with the title "Doomsday falls out".
The anthem on YouTube is already very popular today. Will it also be heard on the benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, provided that everything works and that the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem is to be sung simultaneously by all performers at all three concerts.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast live together in a direct connection from Czech television.
The text of the hymn comes from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, and Xindl X also sings with ...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is due to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We try to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most of us are interested in working with us and have fun.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the barrier-free education centre Studeo, which we have been working on for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built in which we move into with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
What criteria did you choose to use?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý perform.
You can find out everything else on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "large events" planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be carried in the luggage compartment. Furthermore, of course, we have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems so far, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad, you have a comparison of how it looks in each country with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than ours, we have witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its beginnings in the East.
Opposite Prague, Moscow is absolutely not barrier-free. It is still unusual there if someone is in a wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even self-evident there that you let a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're still hanging out on...
It should be noted, however, that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not very common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in the social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come out of our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in engaging with something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, I founded a music group together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, Láća Angelovič, used to say, it's a little out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us, and we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if one does something and this cannot be seen externally, one's own performance does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good reviewers, high-quality equipment, etc.
Was it your goal to get this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I've felt the potential that you can do things differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
Of course, the first impression the viewer usually has is compassion; that's only natural...
But this pity is absolutely unnecessary because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we must regret.
They are people who can live a full life and develop if they have the means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not just a step forward for themselves, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you must not compromise in many things and must also demand a certain discipline.
However, I think this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic performances, and when they find that they have rehearsals twice a week, that they have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert trips, the enthusiasm disappears quickly with many.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láća Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go.
Whoever has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
