The movie Argo: When it's the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had maintained the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have severely damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to free hostages made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by the director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story, which gave the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity - they traveled disguised with Canadian passports as members of a film staff allegedly visiting film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by the exfiltration expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the camouflage credible, articles on this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time, based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This alters the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic contemporary photographs, and there are no big differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions -- men in suits at the meeting table, on the floor, on the phone...
With this film, Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable re-launch of his career.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime thriller No children's play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film that doesn't play in the director's home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that removed the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the initial sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the sense of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also have a similar effect in fictional scenes (the wrong film stick on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the few he works quite successfully, whereby he sometimes helps the reality - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes, in which the imminent crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted from a telephone call in America, or also the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its over-wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and thus they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck's film loses some traction. It's a film that you can follow with some interest, and you can goout the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70th years.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive in a certain way to this day and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of the almighty and omniscient secret services are, it is sufficient.
Guidelines for inflating balloons, bananas and circuses
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which publishes an annual survey of the most absurd bank charges, has decided this year to organise the competition "Absurdest regulation or idea from the EU workshop".
"The EU's recent plan to introduce a 40% female quota in the management of large European companies brought us on this idea," said Patrik Nacher, who is responsible for organising this survey, to the Právo newspaper.
Among the nominated absurdities, for example, is the European Court of Justice ruling on the harmonisation of insurance tariffs for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they are objectively a lower risk for insurance companies.
"Other incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place until the end of February 2013,' said Nacher.
One of the controversial EU regulations is the mandatory incorporation of bioethanol into fuels which, as a result, are damaging to nature, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers, just because they contain a relatively small amount of this dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs much more expensive this year.
In the past, criticism was also reaped by the actual ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the ban on selling conventional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of this or that lobby of trade and industry, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more member states (for example, the Czech Republic is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks with a veto threat).
Lobby interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest trade class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have "curvature anomaly".
The European Commission defended itself with the argument that it only harmonises the inconsistent national standards that would hinder trade.
The EU has already softened the standards on fruit and vegetables against the resistance of some countries, pointing out that the existing directives would lead to food waste.
A candidate for the victory in this survey may be the EU regulation of last year, which according to balloons must be indicated when selling, that children under the age of eight must not inflate the balloon without the supervision of an adult.
The EU relied on an American study that according to balloons is the leading cause of children's suffocation death.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to 14 years of age when using fairground tortoises.
Curious ideas are also at home
A directive that concerns European officials themselves is also relatively absurd - anyone who has an official role in the EU must not use the name Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the issue for Greece and must instead say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In cooperation with the association of liberal economists, Laissez Faire, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com nominated the above-mentioned absurdities as well as the EU regulation on the scope of food stocks in the territory of a member country.
The EU thus set the maximum amount of food stocks that could be found on the Czech Republic's territory on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the fixed volume for preserved mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a high fine.
The organizers of the survey were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or by the idea of providing funding for applications for funding.
Of course, these ideas did not come from Brussels, but from Prague.
"We are disadvantaged by the fact that we do not have a sea.
We will apply for a refund from the EU", said the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he argued that the cereal harvest was very high and that the state warehouses were overcrowded as a result of so-called intervention purchases.
As the Czech Republic has another way to seaports, according to Palas, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
Finally, the European Commission came to the point where the Czech Republic organised an invitation to tender for the purchase of cereals from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The Ministry of Regional Development, under the direction of Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), offered funding for applications for funding to the municipalities, specifically for the placement of grant applications to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
However, some experts believe that while regulations are easily the target of criticism in the Member States, the EU's efforts to regulate and thus also to ensure the effectiveness and development of the European Union as a whole deserves more recognition.
In the opinion of these experts, a more serious problem is the EU funding for projects which have nothing at all in common with the deepening of European integration, but which were forced by individual Member States during the budgetary negotiations.
Emotions also evokes in this country the fact that the Czech Republic, like other Member States in Brussels, has to fight for the right to use specific names of traditional products and does not always win this fight.
The Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky" after a six-year fight with Germany and Austria, the national centre (Tuzemský rum), whose tradition dates back to the 19th century, but our manufacturers had to rename "Tuzemák".
The term rum may only be used for products of sugar cane distillate, not for products of sugar beet.
In the official list of products registered in the EU, the company of the world-famous cheeses Feta and Gorgonzola, the Lübeck marzipan or the Parma ham now includes the Karlovy Vary Zwieback, carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, or the Saaz hops.
With an EU brand, the Pardubic gingerbread or Hořicer rolls can boast.
