"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician in a nearby large company, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder what we need a library for today.
All have Internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to one of those old-style libraries on their own today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town that is hardly to be visited at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest rate of education in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to reconstruct the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro notes as nicely pinned reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to become the master of statistics: a library must come!
Winy Maas from Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of the bold bar charts and producer of funny, even cynical buildings, took the matter with usual serenity and appeared at the competition hearing anno 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin in the face.
And while the jury was still dazzling and looking around and twitching with the armpits, the cheeky Maas piled up his exquisite souvenirs of size to a pyramid and ended his actionist-backed speech with the words: "Dear town community!"
So this is my proposal for the Book Mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is piled up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjoining residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, Buchenberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This makes the faceless small town resort, which up to now had no more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, however, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long way to the book
The first impression: Bücheldorado under cheese bell.
There is indeed a lift that leads through the mountain massif, but the true pleasures of space and reading open up when climbing the topography on foot.
The all-round glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights speak the language of a public city square unequivocally.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally, the bookshelfs stand along the façade, and in the middle there is a large, dark room, which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and pushed the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Buchenberg is cleverly used: offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology center are located in the center.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelfs, which are sometimes wall cladding, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stairs railings.
Optics, haptics and smell are foreign.
Even incarnate architects and civil engineers shake their heads about the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, upon request of the standard.
And so one day, in a Frisian farm, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years, in the Netherlands, greenhouses and fields have used a millimeter-thin plastic fleece as root substrate.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ready for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed to four centimeters thick plates.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material, which smells a bit of new cars and a bit of sports shoe.
After 105 steps you have reached the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-metre-long walk you will be rewarded in the literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and stuffed ficus trees.
They provide atmosphere, but above all for the right humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology despite the many glass surfaces," says Trouborst.
Heat and cool with geothermal heat.
Although the Buchenberg is under a glass fall, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly inside.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand across the glass facade, serve as shading and absorb a large part of the solar radiation.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest are done by fully automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial sceptic from the IT industry, already dared to enter the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls the Boekenberg Spijkenisses "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library - currently 70,000 pieces - are to be filled.
The concept has come up.
The shelves are filled to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
MVRDV has thus succeeded in the supreme discipline that is called in the jargon of identity foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany has to be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
That's because it's just surrounding its foreign policy, away from a policy that has been managed, so to speak, by the US, to a German foreign policy.
What is more, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still touching on their role, but they're on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like France or Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude of the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
That is why it must be careful not to throw the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
It certainly matters.
But I wouldn't want to put too much weight on it either, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great deal of understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break, as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even have some respect for it.
Because it signals that as an international player it must be taken seriously and its interests taken into consideration.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly voted in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic politics, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly has quite a lot of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they can't be part of a broader line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that the Germans know that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany want to play a leading role at all?
Or is Germany still finding it difficult to lead?
Germany is not used to it yet, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a bigger role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a larger role, a variety of anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
This is how Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be receptive to various neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now the US's influence in European politics is steadily diminishing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum right now, who else is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, they're uncomfortable and make them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America work together on the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
