But what is Armani Polo?
There is an officially registered name in China, which has nothing to do with the companies of origin.
Nevertheless, it enjoys protection as long as the actual namesakes do not complain.
And even then it is not clear whether they are right.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, who specializes in protection violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case lands on my desk.
The imitators already have a few additional letters to register their brands.
So Gucci becomes simply Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada one lets Prada-Kny enter.
German companies are also legally copied in this way, such as the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a folder with registrations of the Trademark Office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company had the Zegna DF Puma trademark protected there, an art name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
It is known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and injured intellectual property.
In the big cities there are multi-storey department stores that sell almost exclusively forgeries.
However, Pattloch's cases are different: on behalf of his clients, he is against the fact that Chinese companies are officially granted the right to use a designation that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call this "Bang Mingpai", a passenger badge.
The word is based on "Bang Dakuan".
That means women fishing rich men.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt
"It's business-damaging, you have to fight it," says Pattloch.
"The brand is diluted, the unique position disappears, the image damage is enormous."
The financial failures and the process costs of the affected industries go into the millions, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to the market research company CLSA, China is the third largest market for luxury goods with a volume of 15 billion euros per year and the fastest growing market.
But deletions of dubious entries in the trademark register are difficult to reach and go into money.
Up to nine years, the procedure can take place, with uncertain outcome.
Pattloch reports on cases in which the court dismissed actions because after the long duration of the contested name had become "market reality".
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he must even pay the plagiarist money because he violated his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle prevails here.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a lawsuit with construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that recently took over the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
The Chinese are therefore allowed to use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star until today.
