Dealing with it costs a lot
As is so often the case in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million applications for trademark protection, almost a third more than in 2010.
This is a record and means that for the tenth time in a row, China is leading the list of new registrations around the world, the agency reports.
This also applies to the stock of all valid trademarks, a total of 5.5 million pieces.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan was collected in fees.
Simplified means that each registration costs an average of 1280 yuan or 160 euros.
To tackle this costs a multiple, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarist.
Although the Germans were able to achieve that its illegal fabrication of imitated vehicle parts was lifted.
However, the imitator continued to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
One had failed to do so, as family names could not be protected in Germany, says Hanno Wentzler, Chairman of the Executive Board of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trademark office CTMO rejected the Munich opposition.
Freudenberg was right in the next two instances, but the opponent continues to fight today.
You have to watch the hell out
Now the matter is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident to bring the matter to a good conclusion, and praises the professionalism of the dishes.
But he also says: "The process is extremely complex and costs us a lot of time, money and nerves."
The internal costs could hardly be quantified, that the company archive even had to look through a hundred years old files in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposite side a "high six-digit euro amount" for settlement in vain.
"You can see how much this is worth to us," says Wentzler.
The dangers in the Far East are even threatening to slip back to Europe.
Then, when imitators secure unprotected marks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather.
The Group has long since abandoned this business segment, yet it was able to avert registration.
"You have to watch the hell out," says Wentzler.
Both he and the lawyer Pattloch advise German companies to be very careful in dealings with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark rights; rather, foreigners should also register in China "everything that is somehow worth protecting," Wentzler says.
Otherwise, this can be much more expensive than registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg was in the last act of his brand drama, then one would probably have to pay the opposite side royalties for its own name, explains Wentzler.
Or we will be pushed out of the market in the segment in question.
