Facts about Sexually Transmissible Infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
The bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhoea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human pappilomavirus, herpes genitalis or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabs belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and Tripper are especially common in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five of all syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, Chlamydia infections, trichomonades, candidiasis (fungal), tripper and human pappilomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults is comparatively low in this country - yet this group accounts for around 20 percent of new HIV infections.
In adolescents, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
In this country, human pappilomaviruses are also common in adolescents.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been falling since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2700 cases.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms indicate a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, lower abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not offer 100% protection.
In part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubricating infections and tight body contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially with frequently changing sex partners.
Most STIs can be cured early on and late consequences can be avoided.
