The ride through the Talysch Mountains is wildly romantic.
The minibus rumbles over the winding road, past densely wooded hills, raging rivers and simple farmhouses.
Everything is green and juicy, you might think you're in the Black Forest.
But this is the deepest south of Azerbaijan, the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
Here lives the Caucasian ethnic group of the Talysh, of which not much is known, except that it speaks perfectly Persian as well as Azerbaijani and is very durable.
The final stop is Lerik.
The small town is bursting with Soviet architecture, which doesn't want to fit into the picturesque mountain landscape.
Tourists from Europe hardly come here, too difficult is the journey from Azerbaijan's capital Baku.
For the 323 kilometers it takes eight hours, because the road is only one lane.
The fabulous wealth the land owes to its oil in the Caspian Sea has not yet arrived here in the province.
But Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has the stuff to attract tourists.
"Baku became famous in May with the Eurovision Song Festival - and next year we will have a festival of the oldest people in the world," says Fatulayeva.
She's the director of the Longevity Museum, probably the only one in the world.
Here the vita of about eight dozen talyshes from the area is documented, the older than 100. Fatulayeva points to a black-and-white photo.
This is my grandfather, he was 120 years old.
At the age of 136 years still a child begotten
But the controversial star of the museum is the shepherd Şirali Müslümov, who is said to have become 168 years old.
However, there is no birth certificate.
And given the oldest documented person, who became 122 years old, Müslümov's age seems extremely dubious.
"In 1805 he was born here in the region, in 1973 he died," explains Fatulayeva.
The man had been married three times and had 23 children, at the age of 136 he is said to have fathered another daughter.
So did Şirali Müslümov account for a few decades at his age?
Rembrandt Scholz, an age researcher at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard of the elderly in Central Asia.
"There are also strikingly many high-aged people in some areas of China, Japan or the Hunza Valley in Pakistan," says Scholz, "and in Sardinia, too, there are extremely many very old men."
However, due to a lack of documentation, no scientific evidence of age was to be provided, especially as civil status registers were missing.
Melted butter every day
The fact is, however, that the people of the region around Lerik are remarkably often of biblical age.
There are currently 20 people older than 100 years.
So why do so many elderly people live here in the south?
The Azerbaijani guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains this with the special genes of the Talyschen.
Museum director Fatulayeva, on the other hand, believes that it is the diet.
But that the calorie-rich diet of the Talyschen should be so healthy, that they love meat, bread and, above all, dairy products and many of them drink a glass of melted butter daily, does not seem plausible from a nutritional point of view either.
Or is it the original way of life that keeps people young? Rubaba Mirzayeva lives in Cengemiran, a tiny village near the town of Lerik.
At the age of 97 she is still comparatively young for these latitudes.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house that is typical of the entire Caucasus region.
She sits on the floor with a butter keg that she tirelessly rolls back and forth.
Eight people live here under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and one daughter, both of whom have long been grandparents.
Also two toddlers jump around.
In the kitchen you can prepare tea, which is served in the typical, bell-shaped Armadu glasses.
Mirzayeva's white teeth stand perfectly in line, under her headscarf she hides long, dark-blonde braids, which her son proudly reveals to us.
I always washed my hair with milk, so they never went out and kept their color.
"I never used shampoo," says Mirzayeva.
Monthly pension is enough to live
She always only ate what came from her own farm, tomatoes, potatoes, peas.
All my life, I haven't bought groceries at the supermarket once.
Then she talks about her husband, who was in the army.
It was the worst after World War II.
But everything got better when the "beloved father" Heydar Aliyew took over the rudder.
The propaganda sounds strange from an old woman's mouth.
But the cult that is driven around the father figure of the nation, who ruled his country like a dictator, knows hardly any borders in Azerbaijan.
He was in power until 2003, and later his son Ilham took over the helm.
After all, there is no need among Azerbaijan's old.
230 Manat (about the same sum in euros) receives Mirzayeva monthly as a pension, for local conditions an amount from which one can live well.
And perhaps Mirzayeva's long-grey son is right: "The old enjoy respect in our culture."
