The U.S. Army Private is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
On Friday, the prosecutor's office tried to find out that army-free Bradley Manning - accused of the greatest disclosure of confidential information in US history - failed to complain about the alleged abuse he suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that there was no complaint about his treatment at any of the weekly visits to Manning's prison officials during their nine-month term in Quantico, Virginia.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the prosecution - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard detention period - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The US Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as a source of information.
In the Friday hearing, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out after their meeting with Manning during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he had served under increased detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as "very professional".
According to Fein, the forms did not contain any complaints about abuse, even though officers had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had spoken orally about his concerns and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they had to deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down "No problems" (after discussing the concerns), and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the thoughts of suicide he had mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to lower his observation status to the "prevention of injuries".
The military testified that it had assigned him this restrictive status - one stage under the risk of suicide - to his and others' protection.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and get rid of the observation status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Naval Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had once become unconscious due to the heat.
Not being allowed to know what was happening to him or to the outside world was incriminating.
"My world shrunk to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and glasses.
Manning said he tried to keep moving, because the day was forbidden to sleep or even to lie down.
He had always had to sleep with light that entered his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards couldn't see his face anymore, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's attorney formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas Military Prison.
On Friday, the judge Manning also asked about an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
During the Friday questioning, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night. He would have tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the officer that he could have used the band of his underpants or flip flops to hurt himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experiences and drastically reduce his detention if he is sentenced to trial before the military court, which is scheduled for the beginning of next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offenses, while other charges that are considered too extreme are to be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend and the prosecutor's office is expected to justify the detention conditions.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the regulations applicable to all prisoners under the highest security arrangements in Quantico.
Indictments against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence on the Internet, the transmission of national defence information and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all counts, he is threatened with a life sentence.
