Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) does not see it that way.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
The house walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York, Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea before a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfactory job but not being able to do it".
Boredom is therefore different from apathy in that the person is not busy, but this wants to be.
In the case of apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists of a "disturbation of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only slowly passing away".
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in English, for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Boredom under the Aspect of Attention", which appeared in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighboring room, which had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
Those who heard the hardly audible television reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, could find no reason for them and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
If you try to focus on a difficult or exhausting task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if one does a monotonous job - "like the search for defective products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that paunching and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people more physically attentive.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a roaring speaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people get bored easier than others.
In order to measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale of boredom susceptibility" in the 1980s.
On the scale are statements such as "Many things I have to do repeat and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys get bored more often than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, Professor of Psychology at the University of Westflorida - especially in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a rather strained bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored at school and did their homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were not at school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentages in terms of boredom have increased or decreased.
He was sure, however, that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers have no major influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it leads to people taking extreme physical risks and falling prey to gambling or drugs to relieve them - that's what studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do right now.
If you're bored and you use this energy to play and cook guitar, you'll be happy.
However, while television can provide happiness in the short term, it evaporates in the long term.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, you can turn it away from boredom. However, it has not learned to talk or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, "Self-control transfers from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to talk, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we view them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even outside of the constant growth in activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the agonizing, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth, people are only looking for a way to shut down and relax.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to deal with once the noise is silent."
In Colorado there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
The 19-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco stands for an offense in Southeastern Colorado, which will soon be legal in this state: the possession of a few marijuana skirts and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, on a September day, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was summoned for possession of drugs and drug supplies - cavalier crimes, each with a fine of 100 US dollars - and received a court meeting.
"We are treated like criminals," says Orozco.
But is he one too?
In the uncertain weeks following the state's decision to legalize small quantities of marijuana for personal use, the response to hundreds of minor drug offences depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of misconduct about marijuana are already dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
The police authorities no longer prosecute adults over 21 years of age for possession to a small extent. This is permitted by law as soon as the new laws enter into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative districts of Colorado have announced that they will continue to pursue existing marijuana needle schemes and still quote people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, agree to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their communities.
