And regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, production, distribution and sale of the drug - with a deadline of 1 December 2013.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is, in any case, ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well suited to orientation," says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington City Spirits Authority.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
"We don't have a real precedent that we can follow," he adds.
The Washington Act, called I-502, enters into force on December 6th, making it the end point of a grey zone in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but the ownership is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified at this time - for example, how to agree on the state's requirement for "appropriate access" to licensed marijuana with the ban on cannabis shops around 300 metres around schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
"Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially the metropolitan area of Seattle," says Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21st, Chief Oates sent an e-mail to his staff in Aurora stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor Marihuanadelikte among persons over 21 years of age, and that the police would "from now on" no longer seek criminal charges for these crimes.
Chief Oates added that the police will continue to enforce urban regulations to regulate the cultivation of medicinal marijuana and continue to persecute drug traffickers.
In Weld County, northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck has a tougher view.
After the vote, he stated that his authority would continue to prosecute cases of marijuana possession, mainly in order to persuade consumers to withdraw.
At present, 119 people have to answer to court for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana, although many have also been charged with other crimes.
