Even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative, the reactions are ambivalent.
The police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer indicate adults for possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending property proceedings.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes," he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the very beginning that it would not be easy to reconcile the personal consumption of marijuana with the complexity of government and legal system.
And the conflicting reactions across the state led to a profound disparity among local officials with regard to the great green experiment.
District prosecutors are a "cultural barrier," says Sean McAllister, a lawyer from Denver, who represents the defendant for Marihuanadelikte in court and is a local spokesman for the national organization for the reform of marijuana laws.
"They have spent such a large part of their lives prosecuting people for still not being able to accept legalization," he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller quantities of marijuana as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are traded as national model cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an age of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at federal level as a criminal offence.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will give in.
Despite several sensational arrests of consumers and salesmen of medical marijuana, the federal government has allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states for the most part.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy advisor to the Obama administration, believes that although detectives are unlikely to enter doors to confiscate smaller amounts of drugs, they are likely to be reluctant to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana operations under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not even waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local municipalities approved moratoriums for new marijuana stores, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the West, decided to ban it for six months, which is likely to be passed next week.
"We don't want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at federal level," says Bob Nicholson, member of the City Council.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We depend on what the community has chosen and not on what the state has chosen.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only university students of today are attacked for their views
It's always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended the university that I once thought was the greatest stamp of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposion that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my move to Worscester College at the end of the 1980s - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my bags again and brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A N Wilson mischievously explained that I had left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, ran because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I had come from a private school.
I had been harassed for only one reason - a reason that seemed to be all the more narrow and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my father Woodrow Wyatt, who had died in the meantime, was an important advisor to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Now, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate right-wing students are suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for equal equality protection, which benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior Common Room (JCR) of Corpus Christi College state that they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable" due to their political views.
They demand a place in their college's equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Her situation was aggravated by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which featured Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
The show featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Student Association of Oxford University, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and bragged with a silver suit and silver-set walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say that they are regarded as "sin-goats for the introduction of higher tuition fees".
20-year-old Luke Black, Vice President of the Conservative Student Association of the University of Nottingham, reported in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing tendency to turn left at universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other."
Samuel Roberts, 21 and history student in Corpus Christi, who initiated the request for greater protection, believes that such a climate is "unpleasant." 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, President of the Conservative Student Association of Oxford, said that she had observed a growing rejection of JCR members against moderate right-wing students.
"This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members," she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I was a member of such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I had arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
In the previous year, the university had voted not to grant an honorary title to Margaret Thatcher, a former student, due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would even have made Stalinists startle.
In the first days of the first semester week, where new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what will happen in the future.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even took part with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners' strike, the privatization and the rejection of the government of sanctions against the apartheid regime of South Africa found their way into the wood-paneled rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English. I had not been prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said the tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled on it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and pretty ugly.
"Do Thatcher followers refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students giggled.
My eyes were filled with tears.
"I suggest they take a few French lessons in your spare time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt told me.
I returned to my room with a hanging head.
That night, I was sitting alone in college at dinner when someone tapped me on the shoulder.
It was an English student from the second year named James, who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is as it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory will be harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it'll be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters pretend to be a Labour party supporter.
In a local pub, I later tried to disguise myself.
I insisted that I didn't agree with Mrs Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who ironically attended the conservative Eton College, said to me, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How did Torie have sex?" one asked me.
They're hitting each other, aren't they?
I felt like homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever manage to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people after dark?
Should I have to turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that were ahead of me stretched in front of my spiritual eye to a purgatory of banishment and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as Tory was Norman Stone, professor of contemporary history, who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only to be a conservative, but also because he had advised Thatcher on foreign policy and had written speeches for them.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincially and pettyly and rejected it for his Marxist-Deterministic historical perspective.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara in Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I started commuting between Oxford and my parents' home and found refuge with more open friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his time in the forties, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said.
They would never do that, not in my city of dreaming towertops.
Even my communist friends have always displayed perfect manners.
His wet eyes were clouded.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure you're just being teased.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also Tory followers, had given in to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, where another historical tutor had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly crushed with shame, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to a "brainwash" and called it "old morons".
The relief lasted only a short while.
It was my father who nailed the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my bunnies gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You're welcome to call me a whiny limp dick.
But no 18-year-old should ever suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford - a university that not only produced 14 Tory Prime Ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to celebrity"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino - Master of Couture", which was opened this week in London, ABC talks with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous customers of the Italian fashion maker.
Somerset House, the former residence of Isabel I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this at the opening of "Valentino - Master of Couture", a grand retrospective for which more than 130 haute couture dresses were put together, created by his "Maison" in the last 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says with his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition is the conclusion of a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clientele.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the stuffy and distant world of the nobility.
In the first hall of this exhibition, which will be on display until March 3, there will be a large number of private letters and photos with the signature of the most exquisite aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margarita of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise from the modest fashion maker in the city of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international jet set.
Being in love with the nobility doesn't have to be a disadvantage.
"At least they don't kick their dicks out on your magnificent carpet, as some beautiful celebrities from pop music do," says Baronin Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s they lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular, generous and elegant host.
"We were all happy when we were invited to his house in Gstaad," explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, close friends with forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred the elegance of fame.
And yet he's a star.
Valeria Mazza, in a dress by Valentino
