Many years ago, after a fashion show at Piazza di Spagna in Rome, we went home to him for dinner.
We were about 20 people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
At every detail of his apartment, the decoration, at the food and at the music one recognized and felt his influence.
"All those invited felt important and loved," recalls the "top model" that began her career at the 1995 Haute Couture Week in Paris.
"He never comes out of fashion because his designs are works of art," she concludes.
Fashion Show of Origin
The life of Garavani is not a story of obsession, rather of mutual love.
He likes people with good upbringing and the highest titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries in Somerset House has been transformed into a glorious 60 meter long catwalk that proposes a roll change: the user takes the place of the model and walks along the catwalk to admire a dreamlike "audience" wearing masterpieces by Valentino, such as the dress Jackie Kennedy chose for her wedding with Aristóteles Onassis, the costumes Monica Vitti wore in "La Notte" or a wool and leather coat belonging to Empress Farah Diba.
In this audience of fashion dolls shine names like that of Sibilla de Luxemburgo, Gloria of Thurn and Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria or Sofía of Habsburg.
Naty Abascal and the fashion maker, 2006
