The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, stony paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by getting sulphur from the volcano Kawah Ijen in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphurous gas emanating from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the steep paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the worn-out carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb in the tortoise speed, keeping the balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocents for every kilo of sulphur they deplete.
When they arrive at the top, they find their way between the tourists, who take pictures like circus monkeys, and run three kilometers to the scales with the tiresome heavy baskets, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which since 1960 exploits the deposits in the volcano and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"As we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who usually makes three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours, after which it is completely finished, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable wage for such an almost inhumane effort, however, is three times what he would earn with field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where the coffee harvest pays 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason as important as sulphur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hinduists, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases.
27-year-old Anto has been putting his life at risk at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left its first mark on him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I will work here for another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in a more than acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent, but life-stricken young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up every morning at two o'clock, because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets with sulfur on their shoulders at the bottom of the crater.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs, and does not supply any equipment to the carriers who work on their own account and are paid for by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera, which the guardians of this nature park, together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) demand from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human tragedies.
"This work is for animals and not for humans," protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he continues "as long as he can" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even if the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners are trapped in the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains about serious diseases ... of course except the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik with his 53 years is only able to carry 50 kg.
Every day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulphur out of the volcano, transported by three trucks across a goat path between the bushes to the Tamansari camp, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," explains Unainik, opening his mouth wide, where some teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the elder also works as a sulfur carrier at the age of 30.
Time is passing, but poverty is stopping generation on generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: those who work as human vices on the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore needs babies to save the economy
