Her creative director Douglas Hamilton says that he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill their "national duty".
This is something just for the Internet, so we had to make it funny and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
When it comes to replanting, we are the worst in the world, so we realized that this is a topic that we had to deal with.
We knew that the government had tried a lot, such as marketing perfume with pheromones or organizing speed dating evenings (fast flirting).
It is possible that many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought: Why don't we make something as creative as possible to tackle this problem, such as composing a rap?
1.2 Children
Anyone who does not take this issue lightly is the government of Singapore.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policy measures to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, prolongs maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in south-east Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was above 2 - which is also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't the Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Agency, says that this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has enabled people to have much more options in terms of life goals and priorities besides getting married and making a family," she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of single persons and to the delay in marriage and births, the result of which is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration in order to counteract the reduction of the population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the barely disguised xenophobia is flourishing against many new immigrants, especially against the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the ruling party in Singapore achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on the economic growth of a nation, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policy, the Singapore example also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
It has already had an impact on the housing market.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoeboxes" that may be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living space of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the lifestyle of the single person and that they deter construction companies from building large apartments for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoeboxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out days and even weeks faster than the larger housing units.
This means that they are much better for our cash flow.
He admits, however, that the new standards provide clearer guidance to developers who had previously been put in the way of obstacles if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, discussions with the Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will not have a major impact.
"People are very stressed out, the apartments and the education are expensive, which is why it is pushed out by many," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It is important for me to have my own money and time," says another, about twenty-year-old man.
Men and women cite their careers, stress and the cost of property and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That is why the Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children - the government can still do so much.
The offline private offline is online private
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "the area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference".
What's private for someone under 16?
How is this definition applied to his everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he poses when he exposes himself to situations on the Internet that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who are often on the net.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "something very own" at the personal level and "to the password and the user" when they applied it to social networks.
"My deepest secrets I wouldn't publish in a post," says ten-year-old Jorge in an attempt to explain the meaning of "private" in websites such as Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that's not mine, or someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, nudes, crimes, or to write insulting or violent comments.
Jorge assures me that he has 35 friends in FB and nine in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I'm just uploading them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can talk quickly to relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
Asked, he answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone had a stranger in mind, he would ignore this.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask, he admits not to know 20 of the people he added to his friend list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to the boy, no one has hinted at him or asked him for his address or telephone number.
"If someone pushes me or asks me to do so, I just remove it from my user account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unknown to experiences that are known today as cyberbullying.
A friend's acquaintance was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the account.
"He just did it in private."
He then explains a number of steps to configure a user account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I'd do that if I didn't like him or if I wanted to get rid of him.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to guide children and young people, it is necessary to understand that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for the search for information, but with the appearance of these pages the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's degree in pedagogy at Yale University, and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants" formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are they, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We're the digital immigrants they're supposed to teach when we're still learning ourselves," he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue, "because we require them to have a defined criterion about what can be spread, published or said, and this at an age where maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be picky when it's most important to them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and young people what privacy is is to ask them questions that make them think.
"To tell you not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then mentions a few ways: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger. Then why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like to publish a photo of yourself, like the one you published by a friend?
Do you know what the others are publishing about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission before when you labeled photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Do everyone need to know what you're doing at any moment?
Another point is to give them to understand that they need to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educator, comments that it is essential that parents carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
When they understand all sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "You shall not speak to strangers".
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and should theoretically be signed by the seven governments present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources at the State and President Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the exam, but then explained that it would be published at some time on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content of the statement was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the image of the Presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulating among journalists was received from the press speakers of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
After that, Peru's presidency sent the media an e-mail with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was Humala's statement and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced before, was not published in spite of a strong press call.
On the official ASPA website, you can see that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems for journalists were in place, but they limited access to information to a large extent.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague, which resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins on Monday in The Hague, in the trial Lima initiated against Santiago to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the ruling on the differences that we are currently bringing to this international court," said Humala together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will continue to be a country that abides by international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts," Piñera added, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
Both Presidents confirmed that they would submit to the IGH, after Colombia had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The Head of State read out the final document stating that 16 decisions were taken and that the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for an investment total of 17 billion dollars.
On the decisions taken, he said that the countries of the Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we will extend the decisions on residence rights."
He stated that action would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant features, but should serve to expand our production output and to show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects designed to improve spatial links in South America, especially in rural and border areas... thus uniting our countries and opening up new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a read-out statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians, located on the transverse axes of their territory from the coast to Brazil, and of which two should provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was stressed at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, in order to treat the maritime conflict respectfully after a judgment of the IGH questioned by Bogotá.
"Maybe I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua will also make talks with Nicaragua necessary," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilised and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the new President of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the Block's defence ministers also met in advance to adopt the 2013 action plan to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even if the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru presides at the time of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn how to integrate its citizens," says Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, today confirmed that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal, with "South America actually learning something from Europe."
Correa, who took part in the 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Lima, told state television in Peru that Europeans were "killed in the Second World War and in other conflicts" and that "today they are practically a fatherland."
In this sense, he defended the project of creating a South American citizenship that will drive the member states of the Unasur.
"The free movement of citizens and workers in all South American countries must be achieved, as is already the case in the Andean Community; however, there are still reactionary sectors that seek a return to the past," he warned.
The President of Ecuador also supported the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OEA) with the aim of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those who have signed the San José Convention on Human Rights.
Those who teach never commit themselves to anything, and in return we always sign everything to the South Americans.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is based in Washington and financed by the United States," he said as an allusion to the political asylum that Ecuador has granted to the founder of WikiLeaks, Julian Assange.
Correa assured him that he did not regret this decision because he had not betrayed his principles, but had complied with his "deep democratic values and views on human rights".
He added that there were "reasonable assumptions at the time that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his proceedings would not be complied with."
He also criticised the Swedish judiciary, which had asked him to interrogate him on his territory for an alleged sexual offence, while "Swedish justice allowed this by means of a video conference that could have been carried out through the Embassy of Ecuador in London."
Correa stated that there was a risk that Assange's health and mental condition would be affected.
"Since he was in our embassy, I have not spoken to him, but the ambassador has informed me that he has a slight problem with his lungs, but not a serious one," said the head of state of Ecuador.
However, there is a danger that he would take physical and mental damage because he was trapped in a narrow space and could not perform physical exercises outdoors.
"This would affect the health of every person," he added.
Correa stated that the asylum solution granted to Assange since June at the Embassy of Ecuador in London was the granting of a free letter to travel to Ecuador, and that this was in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European legal authorities. He underlined that there had been talks with London to find a solution for the imprisoned founder of WikiLeaks.
We are not dealing with human rights, we are not using that word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European legal authorities, because the lawyer of Assange, Baltazar Garzón, is conducting a series of proceedings at various European institutions," he said.
And "if Britain grants this license tomorrow, I think it's done."
And if Sweden interrogated Mr Assange at the Embassy of Ecuador in London or via Skype, as the Swedish case law allows and in other cases was done, the problem would be resolved.
Correa took the opportunity to confirm himself as a defender of the freedom of the press and said that what he does not tolerate is "the mediocrity, evil intention, and the lie that defies freedom of expression."
"The biggest enemies of freedom of the press are not the evil and perverted politicians, but bad journalists who strive for profit and blackmail," he said.
In this sense, he congratulated Ecuador for not being dominated by such journalists "and not by bankers or hegemonic and petty-bourgeois countries," and anticipated that, in re-election, "he would deepen the revolution in order to continue the path in this right direction."
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in the Unasur at least until his next elections, arguing that the organism "must remain hard and must not allow opportunism and no coup d'état disguised as legal" because it "destroyed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay."
The President of Ecuador also considers the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, now and after the judgment of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, which favoured the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime borders between the two countries, to be "absolutely entitled."
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They must be treated comprehensively so that they can be overcome and looked forward.
He also trusted in a good conclusion to the disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile before the same Court of Justice and said that "it is right for Latin America to call on international authorities if both countries commit themselves to accept the judgment, even if it is very harsh."
With regard to the possibility that he would stand as a candidate for the next presidential election in Ecuador in order to reach his third consecutive mandate, he stated that he sees this possibility "with much optimism and joy, although it is sometimes very difficult."
Correa assured that if he lost the elections in February 2013, he would withdraw from political life.
Power has never interested me personally, but under such unjust circumstances as in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement had the belief that I was the one who guaranteed this likely victory, so I have to live up to this responsibility," he said.
If I were to win, it would be my last period as president, after which I withdraw from public life.
This also applies if we lose.
"That's decided," he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the President of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I have just spoken to the Vice-President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, who told me that he had travelled there for planned, routine treatment and that he would be expected to be able to return to Cuba after the election campaign.
"In no case does it mean a relapse in President Chávez's state of health," he commented.
