Cause of dying because of AIDS is a too late detection today
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed with the result: HIV-positive.
"It was as if a bomb hit," he says about the moment he got the diagnosis that the doctor tried to "weaken" without discernible success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inform himself about it; and this with such commitment that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine at the beginning of the 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
At that time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye, "because it led to a dead end."
At that time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome even with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who do not know about their illness and who have already caused damage to the virus and exhausted their immune system, and who are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient taking up treatment in good time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of HCG's HIV unit, saying that this information was supported by a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
The specialist in infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008 the scientists have concluded that although AIDS is not a death sentence, the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system of individuals at the beginning of the treatment, and that those who are not addicted to drugs have greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above remarks mean that those who receive HIV-positive diagnosis at the age of 25 can "be 75 years of age without problems as long as they are under control," said this expert.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is on average 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA annual report), it is true that since the appearance of AIDS, 60% of the patients recorded in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May of this year there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that universal access to antiretroviral medicines has been available since 2005.
- So why are people still dying?
In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years, we have had no medical care problems. The problem is that people are in a very advanced state because they don't know their state of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. To be able to influence global mortality, more early diagnosis is required, which is why all persons who require this must be offered massive detection tests."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS Avoidance in Jalisco) and also the patients like Fabrizio, who had his test carried out in a private laboratory, for the only reason that it had made a friend of him who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi sarcoma (a cancerous tumor), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, it's better to burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was for improvement, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, just like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," Fabrizio points out, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO in order to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today in the context of the global AIDS day.
They should do the test if they belong to the risk group. The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, journalist from Guadalajara, who has taken on the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the places designated for this "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; in the past they were delivered individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Adolescents are at risk for new infections.
"What do you need them for?" is a widespread ridicule question by social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and the health care system, which young people do not want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should not only be located behind the counter, but also in output devices in public toilets of facilities frequently visited by young people.
It is not intended to promote promiscuity.
They are not to be paid the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question whether preservatives would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality does not look like this; it is best to bring condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity," he put it to the point.
Key data of Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is in fourth place nationally in new and cumulated AIDS cases, and 13th in relation to HIV.
92% of contagion is caused by sexual intercourse, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people who do not know for each registered case.
After the Court of Appeal of the United States has confirmed a judgment that does not recognise the restructuring of the liabilities of the Vitro Group, which has been reached through a commercial exchange rate in Mexico, an ominous precedent will be created for any national company with branches in the neighbouring country that has payment problems.
So one could say that the procedures for the survival of the companies that allow Mexican laws are not valid in the country of the stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the recognition of the judgment given on 15 June by Judge Harlin Hale at the court in Bancarrotas for the Northern District in Texas results in Mexican companies being helplessly exposed to confiscation of their property beyond the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens the door to the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the United States Supreme Court for three inconsistencies.
While the judge of the case points out that creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy law of the United States, the Court of Appeal of the Fifth Circuit, based in New Orleans, first of all states that the main proceedings are the commercial exchange rate dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in procedures for the insolvency of companies with a cross-border profile is not known.
In fact, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law was established, with the American Law Institute being used as a mediator.
Secondly, the judgment states that, without the votes of the companies, after recognition of the liabilities in the assets of the Vitro branches with their parent company, the necessary majority would not have been achieved for the restructuring of the liabilities.
However, this possibility is recognised by Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case where this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities have been confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Federal Institute for Trade Prices).
It is also true that after the withdrawal of the votes of the branches, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who sued Vitro in the courts of the United States, i.e. the vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have achieved a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for its difficult situation as of 2008 in the context of the major economic crisis in the United States, which struck the country.
For this reason, the González Sada family appeals to the same Court of Appeal in order for the vote to take place in plenary, i.e. by all judges, because only three of them voted.
If this is not granted, the Cerciorare appeal, which calls for the review of the proceedings by a higher authority, is brought in this case by the Supreme Court of the United States.
The most serious thing about this case is that the court dismissed a document sent by the Mexican Government under the Figura amicus curiae (friend of the court) describing the proceedings carried out by Vitro under the Trade Concourse Act, pointing out that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries in order to comply with Chapter 15 of the Bankruptcy Act of the United States.
It is also noted that the country has been subject to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules on cases of cross-border insolvency which guarantee equality between debtors and creditors.
Two-banded carambole: a blow for Vitro and for the country.
