Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The globetrotter of basketball, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, was connected to basket sports for more than 60 years and travelled the whole world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a great intellectual collection of the history of basketball in the country as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for six years, whether as a player of lower classes, a player of the first national league, an agent and head of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Association.
"I've spent my life putting on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time when I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the association in the 1990s," Reyes recalled when visiting Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes doesn't exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those that recall his time at the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, where he celebrated his 15th anniversary as a co-manager or managing director of the club.
"These were my best years I've enjoyed the most because I've been part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as managing director, co-manager or coach.
They were many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye with a 1981 championship, the year of Jerome Mincy's debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good administrator," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me, "I have a very strong and 2 m tall player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended the free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who allowed himself to become a citizen and was one of our best throwers.
I remember he said that if Mincy had made Bayamon a championship, Gausse would take care of another one.
He was awarded the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but already from a distance, because he was already in the top position of the association in 1988.
At that time he preferred to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we first won the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico against the United States.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we took fourth place, which should have been bronze, if it hadn't been this Canadian referee who let us repeat the last move for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is among the best, as well as those who won against the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is the team of the 1991 Pan-American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered the US team a fight, as they did when they won bronze against us at the World Cup.
Not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz) were there again, but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be there in 1990 due to a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which gave us great pleasure was that of the 1995 pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner as a substitute for the blocked players because of the events at the Pan-American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against every prognosis.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was without a doubt Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
Nobody in Puerto Rico has dominated this level like Piculín.
And this, without taking into account his career in the various leagues in which he played.
Who was the best coach from Puerto Rico?
That's a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
Of the boys, I like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you think is the best you've achieved in the bandage?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN in the early 1990s up to 17 teams in one season.
What else do you have to do?
There are things that I would have introduced, such as the regionalisation of the lower categories.
That the boys in Ponce, for example, only play in their area and only meet teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Today the children make unnecessary many trips and games.
At least I see the result of the prescribed training and courses for coaches, table officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like listening to music, watching videos of music of my time on YouTube, enjoying my grandchildren and sometimes I go to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always by my side.
